<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>4 Beresford Avenue</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from Freight on Rail (CYS0111)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Freight on Rail thanks the Transport Select Committee for the opportunity to comment on its </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">follow up </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">inquiry into</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> cycling safety</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  We are commenting on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of the subject headings.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Freight </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on Rail, a partnership of the rail freight industry, the transport trade unions and Campaign for Better Transport, works to promote the economic, social and environmental benefits of rail freight to local and central Government.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">What central and local Gove</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">rnment could do to improve cycling safety. Ideas could include better training and advice for drivers and cyclists, better enforcement of the law applying to drivers and cyclists, and better vehicle and road infrastructure.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Lack of enforcement of road regu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">lations with regard to HGVs add</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> to dangers.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Improved enforcement of vehicle standards would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">help </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ensure that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">all lorries meet legal guidelines </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">which are designed for safety reasons. The r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">oad haulage industry has a poor record in complying with existing r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">oad regulations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> which puts other road users, especially cyclists, at added risk.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In the UK,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">83% of HGVs exceeded their speed limit of 50 mph on dual carriageways and over 70% exceeded the 40 mph limit on single carriageway roads. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Source DfT Vehicle speeds</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> 2011</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK road side weight checks had a 58% overloading rate. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Source FTA Logistics Report 2012</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Whether it would be desirable and feasible to segregate cyclists from other road users, including, for example, by prohibiting HGVs from entering city centres at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">peak hours.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In analysing cycling fatalities involving HGVs it is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">important to look at Government policy about HGV safety holistically. For example it is r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">elevant to examine HGV involvement in all road fatalities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> because </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">there are serious inconsistencies in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Government policy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with regard to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">HGV</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> safety which could make cycling more dangerous. Therefore the following issues need to be taken into account:-</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1. HGV involvement in fatalities is rising as other categories of fatal collisions reduce.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2. DfT authoris</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed ten year trials of 7ft longer HGVs are more dangerous to cyclists</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3. Impact on cyclists of increasing HGV single carriageway speeds to 45 or 50 mph.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4. Impact on cyclists of Government policy allowing cross border traffic of mega trucks in the revision </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of European Weights and Measures Legislation </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1. General picture of HGV involvement in fatalities is rising </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Lorries are involved in a increasing percentage of fatal traffic accidents on Britain's roads. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">MTRU analysis using DfT statistics </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">show</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> HGVs were implicated in more than half of fatal motorway accidents and one-in-five fatal accidents on A-roads</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> continuing negative trends over the last five </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">years.</span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This new research shows lorries are involved in a high percentage of the most serious a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ccidents on our roads and that the problem is getting worse. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Therefore, we believe t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he Government should be taking steps to reduce the dangers posed by lorries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> instead of introducing initiatives to al</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">low </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">7ft </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">longer lorries and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">considering </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">higher speed limi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ts for HGVs on single carriageways</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, for example</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The assessment of official statistics, carried out by the Metropolitan Transport Research Unit (MTRU) for Campaign for Better Transport, showed that the ratio of fatal road accidents involving Heavy Good Ve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hicles (HGVs) compared with those involving other vehicle types has been climbing year on year:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 23.8pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">On motorways: More than half (52%) of fatal accidents on motorways involve HGVs, despite HGVs only making up 10% of the traffic on motorways </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 23.8pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">On A-roads: HGVs a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">re involved in 1 in 5 fatal crashes on A roads, a ratio that has worsened over the last 5 years </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 23.8pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">On minor roads: An HGV is five times as likely to be involved in a fatal accident on a minor road than other traffic </span></li></ul><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt; width:321.9p