ight-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:76.3pt"><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2012</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:147.1pt"><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">52.3</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:98.5pt"><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">10.9</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Source DfT traffic statistics</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Trials of 7ft longer lorries which are more dangerous to cyclists and other vulnerable road users than existing HGVs</span><br /><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">After pressure from the road haulage industry, t</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he Government allowed trials of longer trailers despite the fact that these vehicles are more dangerous to cyclists </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and other vulnerable road users </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">than existing HGVs</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> especially on urban roads</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In fact, the </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Government did not even evaluate the impact on cyclists.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The then Minister, Mike </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Penning</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> state</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d in Parliament on 15</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> September 2011 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">the risk is not there for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">cyclists </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">despite the fact that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a subsequent PQ showed that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the Government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">did not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">disaggregate the risk by road user</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The revised Impact Assessment published with the Government's Report on the Consultation into longer semi-trailers does not disaggregate the safety risk between different categories of road user”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">(</span><a href="http://www.theyworkforyou.com/wrans/?id=2011-11-22b.81709.h"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">www.theyworkforyou.com/wrans/?id=2011-11-22b.81709.h</span></a></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Government’s own tests showed that the new longer lorries </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">7ft (</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.05 metres</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> longer which are 18.55m long, have a greater tail swing, increased driver blind spots and inferior manoeuvrability which makes them more dangerous to cyclists.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Many urban junctions would simply not be able to accommodate these longer trucks, forcing them </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to mount kerbs, traffic islands or enter adjacent lanes when turning. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Therefore, it is imperative that the longer HGVs are restricted to designated local authority routes agreed by the local authority and the operator. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CBT </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">research,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">shows that because of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">their reduced manoeuvrability, particularly while cornering (known as out-swing) these trailers are unsuitable for many of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">urban </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the roads on which they are being used. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CBT and the Technical Advisers’ Group has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">written to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Secretary of State calling on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">him to give local authorities the right to dictate which routes these lorries can travel on. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As the DfT consultation stated, the new longer lorries, which are up to 18.55 m long, have a greater tail swing [1] and larger driver blind spots than existing 16.50 m trucks. The demonstration of the 18.55 m HGV at Millbrook on June 27th 2013 confirmed th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">at the longer HGV has inferior manoeuvrability compared with the existing 16.50 m lorries which makes negotiating tight turns on urban roads even more difficult . A demonstration of the new longer vehicle at the Department for Transport’s testing facility </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in Millbrook Bedfordshire showed the rear tail-swing when turning corners was significantly greater than normal HGVs, up to 1.3  m greater under normal road conditions, and would occur within the driver’s blind spot, posing a significant threat to other ro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ad users. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> During the consultation, DfT officials had confirmed that the 18.55 m longer HGV, while meeting existing standards does not have the turning performance of existing 16.5 m HGVs.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">DfT research stated 7ft longer trailer would have increased tail </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">swings and be more susceptible to cross-winds. P8 para 28. DfT Longer Semi-trailers Feasibility Study.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The DfT research states that the longer lorry could meet existing standards with either 2 self-steer axles or a command steer axles but meeting existing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> standards is not the same things as meeting existing performance Page 7 paragraph 23 DfT Feasibility Study 2011. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Reviewing HGV speed limits on single</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">carriageway roads</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Government is also showing signs of ceding to industry demands on speed limits for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lorries. Currently, HGVs are limited to 40mph on single carriageway A-roads. Government recently consulted on plans to raise this to 45 or 50mph and is expected to make an announcement shortly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Increasing speed of HGVs will make them more dangerous for cyc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lists.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Threat of mega trucks 82 ft long </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">from revision of European directive 96/53</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In the current revision of the directive 96/53 governing weights and dimensions of HGVs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> which is currently being considered by the Parliament and Council</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, the European Commission has proposed allowing cross border traffic of mega trucks between consenting countries. The industry is pushing for double articulated mega-trucks to be allowed on UK roads even though the Commission has admitted that these 25 met</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">re trucks can worsen road safety. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In the Netherlands which allows mega trucks in national traffic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">its Government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">stated that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">should only be allowed on roads with a separate infrastructure for cyclists</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> which does not exist on most UK roads Source </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">Marc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">h 2010 Monitoring traffic safety Rijkswaterstaat, Ministry of Transport, Public Works and Water Management</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">And Dutch </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Government experts acknowledged serious hazards of mega trucks for cyclists.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">SWOV, the Dutch national road safety </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">esearch Institute has shown that lorries with trailers have an almost equal if not greater risk of accidents occurring on the side of the lorry or trailer and thereby doubling the risk that cyclists face </span><a name="_ednref1"></a><a href="#_edn1">[i]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">While it is welcome that the UK Government has st</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ated that it will not allow 25 metre mega trucks on UK roads, the reality is that it will come under huge pressure from the road haulage industry again to allow these massive HGVs on competition grounds. Therefore</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the only way to stop mega trucks is for th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK Government to oppose European plans for these huge lorries to be allowed to cross national borders</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, which it is not currently planning to do</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">All the UK cycling organisations are opposed to mega trucks as is the European Cyclists’ Federation which re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">presents their European interests. ECF stated in its briefing – gigaliners/mega trucks and road safety for cyclists January 2012 that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">However despite the lack of clear empirical evidence we believe </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">that there would be increased road safety issues concernin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">g blind spots; manoeuvrability and handling; infrastructure damage and changes.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">  </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For more information go to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">http://www.freightonrail.org.uk/MegaTrucksBriefingMay2013.htm</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Philippa Edmunds January 2014</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_edn1"></a><a href="#_ednref1">[i]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic"> http//www.swov.nl/rapport/R-2008-11A.pdf</span></p></body></html>